                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d34">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/1827: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at Nanking</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-09-22T18:00:00-04:00"
                            >September 22, 1931—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>75. Your 624, September 22, 3 p.m.<note n="37" xml:id="d34fn37">Reference is to
                        telegram from the Minister in China, <ref target="#pg_26">p.
                        26</ref>.</note> First, the Secretary of State has not made the statement
                    attributed to him; second, the American Government was in no way consulted or
                    informed in advance. You may so inform your interlocutors.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
